ng Roman joke book—Mary Beard tracks down the giggles, smirks, and guffaws of the ancient Romans themselves. From ancient "monkey business" to the role of a chuckle in a culture of tyranny, she explores Roman humor from the hilarious, to the momentous, to the surprising.  But she also reflects on even bigger historical questions. What kind of history of laughter can we possibly tell? Can we ever really "get" the Romans’ jokes?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLatin wit and humorxHistory and criticism. 0aLaughterzRomexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aancient literary criticism.  aancient rome.  aanthropology.  aapproachable scholarship.  aclassical literature.  aconversational.  acultural studies.  aessays on rhetoric.  afunny.  ahistory of ancient rome.  ahistory of laughter.  ahistory.  ahumor and drama.  ahumor.  ainviting.  ajokes.  alaughter.  aliterary analysis.  amonkey business.  aperforming arts.  apurpose of laughter.  aroman culture.  aroman history.  aroman humor.  aroman joke book.  aroman writing.  asather classical lectures.  atheories of humor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027716840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095820340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958203423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958203/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY